[3] New York: alert
Date: Tue 25 Apr 2017
Source: 6 News CBS Albany, WRGB [edited]
http://cbs6albany.com/news/local/columbia-county-issues-rabies-warning


The Columbia County Department of Health (CCDOH) is warning people not to handle, capture or attempt to confine any wild animals.

It's due to recent incidents involving contact between county residents and animals that have tested positive for the rabies virus. Recent cases cited by the agency include exposure to a rabid fox and raccoon.

The DOH says not only does attempting to handle wild animals pose a health risk, it is illegal under New York State law. CCDOH hosts several free rabies clinics for cats, dogs, and ferrets throughout the year to keep animals safe.

There is no charge to Columbia County residents, however donations are accepted.

The next rabies vaccination clinic for 2017 has been scheduled for:
[Sat 6 May 2017] Gallatin Town Highway Garage County Routes 8 & 11
Cats and Ferrets 10:00 - 11:00
Dogs 11:00 -12:00 Copake Vets

Dates and times for additional rabies clinics are available on the Columbia County Department of Health website (http://www.columbiacountyny.com; select "Department Links" to find the Health Department), or by calling the Health Department at (518)828-3358.

