[6] Delaware: feline, human exposure
Date: Wed 5 Apr 2017 727 PM EDT
Source: Delaware online, The News Journal [edited]
http://www.delawareonline.com/story/news/health/2017/04/05/cat-tests-positive-rabies-bridgeville-area/100098258/


A cat that tested positive for rabies has been euthanized after coming into contact with at least one person and possibly infecting others in the Bridgeville area [Sussex County], according to authorities.

The Delaware Division of Public Health (DPH) warned residents of Main Street and the intersecting roads of Fawn Road and Redden Road that the DPH lab had found the animal to be rabid on Wednesday. The cat is the 1st lab-confirmed rabies case of the year [2017] in which humans may have been exposed, officials said. Since January [2017], DPH has performed rabies tests on 23 animals, 3 of which were confirmed to be rabid, including the cat, 1 raccoon, and 1 dog.

[...]

Health officials ask those who think they might have been bitten, scratched or come in contact with the rabid cat's saliva or that of another feral in the area to immediately contact their health care provider or call the DPH Rabies Program at (302) 744-4995.

Health officials said traps were being placed in the area to catch any feral cats that may have been exposed. Health officials say residents should take precautions against rabies by:
- avoiding wild and feral animals;
- ensuring their pets are up to date with rabies shots;
- keeping pets indoors or, while outside, supervising them on a leash;

Warm spring and summer temperatures lead to more outdoor activities, which increases possible exposure to rabies through contact with animals such as bats, raccoons, skunks, and foxes.

Rabies in humans and animals cannot be cured once symptoms or signs appear. If the animal is of unknown origin or unavailable to be quarantined or tested, the Division of Public Health recommends people receive post exposure prophylaxis treatment, a series of 4 vaccinations, as a precautionary measure.

Health officials recommend members of the public help prevent the spread of rabies by vaccinating all pets and livestock. All dogs, cats, and ferrets 6 months and older are required by Delaware law to be vaccinated against rabies. Vaccinating valuable livestock and horses also should be considered. Animals that have frequent contact with humans should be vaccinated.

Here are some tips:
- pet owners can reduce the possibility of pets being exposed to rabies by not letting them roam free;
- spaying or neutering pets may reduce the tendency to roam or fight and thus reduce the chance they will be exposed to rabies;
- do not feed or water your pets outdoors; bowls can attract wild and stray animals;
- keep your garbage securely covered;
- do not handle unfamiliar animals, including cats, and dogs, even if they appear friendly.

For more information on the Delaware Division of Public Health's rabies program, visit http://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/dpc/rabies.html or call (866) 972-9705 or (302) 744-4995. For more information on rabies, visit the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention at http://www.cdc.gov/rabies/.

[Byline: Alonzo Small]

