[7] Mexico (Yucatan): canine, human exposure
Date: Wed 12 Apr 2017
Source: The Yucatan Times [edited]
http://www.theyucatantimes.com/2017/04/health-authorities-find-an-outbreak-of-rabies-in-progreso/


After confirming a positive case of canine rabies, found by the Central Regional Laboratory of Mérida on [Fri 7 April 2017, the Yucatán Health Secretariat (Secretaría de Salud de Yucatán, SSY, in Spanish) established an operation for its control in the municipality of Progreso.

The state coordinator of the SSY Zoonosis Program, Daly Gabino Martínez Ortiz, said that the head of the unit, Jorge Mendoza Mézquita, ordered the immediate application of the procedures from the guide for the care of rabies and NOM-011-SSA2-2011 (Mexican standard normative for rabies control), for the prevention and containment of human rabies, as well as in dogs and cats.

Martínez Ortiz detailed that it was a 3 year old female pit bull dog, owned by a man from the zone, which had positive [results] to the application of direct immunofluorescence technique. [Rabies is tested in deceased animals, not living animals. - Mod.TG]

Its owner revealed that he adopted the animal when it was a month old and did not have the current vaccination. He explained that when he was handling the pet, it caused him a shoulder injury, so he already receives the indicated treatment.

The official remarked how important vaccination is to dogs' health and urged people not to lower their guard or neglect the care and feeding of these animals, especially in the seasons of very high temperatures.

The preventive actions in Progreso include a vaccination campaign for all the dogs and cats of that area.

On 30 Mar 2017, another case of rabies was reported, at that time in the town of Hoctún [Yucatán]. The specimen was a 5 month old dog, that had not been vaccinated, also owned by a family from the town, the reason why the SSY arranged an operation of vaccination in an area up to 5 kilometers [3.1 mi] radius of the municipality.

Martínez Ortiz added that, according to the regulations, these activities were extended to the towns of Xocchel and Tahmek [Yucatán], where anti-rabies vaccination is carried out at each house of the both towns.

He also noted that at Hoctún there have been detected 4 contacts with humans, 1 of which was accidentally with the animal's snout, which caused an injury in the right hand of the affected. For all cases, the corresponding treatment has already begun.

The last outbreak of this disease in Yucatan was recorded in the town of Seyé, in 2014.

